sudo-
The sudo command is one of the most important and powerful tools in Ubuntu (and other Unix-like systems).
It stands for "superuser do" and allows a permitted user to execute a command as another user, typically the root user.

* basic syntax
amol@amol-HP-ProBook-440-G3:~$ sudo [options] command

*Example

amol@amol-HP-ProBook-440-G3:~$ sudo apt update

amol@amol-HP-ProBook-440-G3:~$ sudo apt upgread

* use case

| Task              | Command                               |
| ----------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| Update packages   | `sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade` |
| Edit system files | `sudo nano /etc/fstab`                |
| Restart services  | `sudo systemctl restart nginx`        |
| Install packages  | `sudo apt install package-name`       |
| Mount drives      | `sudo mount /dev/sdX /mnt`            |
| Change ownership  | `sudo chown user:user file`           |

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
* Run as Another User

amol@amol-HP-ProBook-440-G3:~$ sudo -u username command
